<font color="#FF0000">IN RESPONSE TO RAY:</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jan 11 13:48:45 US/Eastern 2001
</tt><p>
I have never been to war and probably never will so I don't know much about actually being there. I think that There are some things that are done in war that are exceptable, in the situation, that wouldn't normally be. On the other hand killing innocent women and Children, that you know are not against you, is very wrong.<br><br>
Things like brutal murders without thinking are something that happens in war, even if it is an inhumane killing, it happens and is expected to happen. People sometimes do other things in war just to keep themselves sane. I think pat is right to say &quot;Judge Not lest you Be Judged&quot;. We have never been there and don't understand the strain that is put on you emotionally through war. On some things we can sit here and easily say &quot;That is an atrocity&quot;, but if we had been through it maybe we would think differently.<br><br>
Though things like killing do happen in war I think there is a line crossed when solgiers shoot innocent people and do things that are not nessecary. I am not saying that all solgiers have done these things but like tourchering an enemy just for fun or killing someone you know is not against you. <br>
      <br>
I can see where some people would think that war and the things that are done are an atrocity but they have to realize that they were not put in that situation. Some things that were done were wrong but some things can be justified by what they went through and what there jobs there were. <br>
  
